segments.text: Down on the fourth floor, it had all kinds of trash and garbage and dirt mixed in with it.
Then on the second floor, it was plenty of water that stayed with us, and we could sweep it down to the first floor, which of course caught it off.
Were there ever any fireworks in the...
I never heard any, don't recall any.
Okay.
Nothing electrical, nothing plugged into a socket.
Not that I recall.
I'll tell you how tight I was.
I had a radio.
I couldn't get it to play.
They said you needed an aerial so I went over and I didn't know what aerial wire was.
So I went over to the store at Northgate.
They told me that the wire that I asked for, I said this is probably what I need.
I didn't know anything.
And it was a regular electrical wire and they said it was 10 cents a foot.
Well I know the nearest tree must have been 50 feet away.
They didn't have five dollars to spend on
So I just told him I'd take three feet and walk out of there with three feet.
Of course, it was absolutely no value.
Later, I found out what aerial wire was and brought some.
The radio never did work well.
Once you became a sophomore, during the war years, was there
very much difference in being a freshman, and were those class differences notable during the war, or were they obscured?
No, no, they were notable.
We knew who sophomores were and juniors and who the freshmen were.

And let's see, as a freshman, I don't think we had any freshmen in our, I think we were really sophomore freshmen, because as I remember, the sophomore and the few juniors and seniors were there all in the same dorm,
I don't think we had any freshmen in our dorm until our junior year.
We had been there in our fifth semester.
So you arrived in late May of 43.
Yes.
And you're there for how long before you go away?
I left at the end of May in 1945, and I went in active duty.
Qualified, had six semesters, and had enough hours to be classified as a senior.
OK. On the serious side.
What did you and your contemporaries think about in your serious moments?
What did you all think was just ahead of you?
Well, y'all knew we were going into service, and that my roommate and I had hitchhiked to Houston and stayed with my folks and enlisted in the Air Force in November of 45, 44.
We weren't called until we had the K-18 to be called up.
I don't know that we thought anything serious.
We paid attention to the war a little bit.
I don't know that we thought much about it.
I don't remember any serious discussions.
Well, did you all think this was like a court trip or that it was a lot more serious than that?
Well, we had fun.
I don't know.
I guess it was fun we had while we were there.
Looking back, I know I enjoyed it.
I don't know how I felt then.
But I don't remember any serious thoughts about the war, except that we wanted to go and be part of it.
I think everybody did.
We wanted to go and be part of it.
Were there any events, world events or otherwise, that you remember while you were at A&M?
Do you remember where you were when you heard the news?
I remember President Roosevelt's death, which I guess everybody that was there did.
Describe that, please.
Coming back from lunch, I guess it was, from Duncan Hall, going back to dorm 7, there was a newsstand, I guess between dorm 9 and the band dorm 11.
I guess it was.
And I remember hearing somebody had a radio or something and told us about it.
I don't know if I was any more impressed than that one way or the other, that Truman was a successor.
don't remember any other thoughts at this moment.
One thing I don't know maybe you've never told about before, but there were concessions on the campus when we were there.
Oh, no.
The YMCA had a Y building, which I guess is still called the Y, and the basement had a soda fountain.
I don't think there was a full drugstore, but a soda fountain, I know.
And then under a big old tree in front of the
Well, I see it would be to the north of the academic building near the ME building and the electrical engineering building, the big oak tree.
And it had a stand there where we could get hot dogs and hamburgers and soft drinks.
And we did a lot of that instead of going to the mess hall at noon.
Or maybe just for snack.
I guess for snack.
And that wasn't a violation of any?
I guess so.
It was fully authorized by the university.
I mean, it was okay for a freshman or a sophomore to- Yeah.
Yeah.
Okay.
I don't remember any problems coming up as a result of it.
And were those the only places on campus to get a snack?
As I recall, those were the only places.
I don't remember any place else.
I don't know of anything that did what the- There might have been, there was another male post office.
near, behind, behind, not Walton, um, well, near what's, across from the trigon today.
And, uh, I'm not sure, maybe it didn't have some drinks in there, but the only thing I remember about that is that we, uh, we had a dance before I left for service, and I had a date.
At that time, I had started dating, which was interesting.
I met her because...
The guy that was a year ahead of me was having an argument with her in Houston one weekend.
And he said, tell her how good a guy I am.
Well, I went to tell her I ended up being here instead of him.
But anyway, we sat on the male ramp that would be unloaded dock high level.
And I thanked her.
And if I were saying goodnight or something, that was the only time I really remember going over there.
During those years before you left,
Were there some memorable teachers, advisors, counselors that you recall?

There was a Dr. Pinkerton, I don't remember his first name, who was head of the aero department when I finally started taking some aero courses, who we were always told was always in contact with the Department of the Army and the Air Force for research projects.
And what was his name?
Did Pinkerton have a nickname?
That is out of my mind.
If it is, prompt me, but I don't remember.
I don't know.
There was another fellow that was so bent over from arthritis, I can't remember his name.
He was an excellent teacher.
I can't remember his name.
There was another guy.
After that escapade at our freshman ball, I had an English teacher.
I think his name was Greer.
I'm not sure.
I went into his class, 8 o'clock, I guess this was Saturday morning, and he had already been sick all night.
He was going to give us a quiz that morning.
Why he picked that morning to give us a quiz after our dance the night before was unfair, but it was done.
And halfway through the exam, it was an English class.
Halfway through, I told him I was sick and had to go outside.
And the only time I ever saw him grimp was when I went outside.
And then I came back, and I failed the course.
He failed, I don't know how many, but most of us, many of us failed this course that year.
Why we failed English, I don't know.
All right, let's see.
English grammar, I wasn't very good at.
All right, other teachers I'm trying to provoke your thought
chemistry, math.
Dr. Harrington was my chemistry teacher.
Describe him.
M.T.
Harrington.
What kind of teacher?
Brilliant lecturer.
Very articulate, as you know, and knew him.
Just made everything in the lecture class
understandable, very easy to comprehend.
I say very easy to comprehend since having had the same book in high school, I guess it made it easier, but just a very personable person.
I didn't know him personally in those years, I met him in later years, but just very relaxed, easy, articulate person, easy to know.
A guy I didn't get along with,
Which is a bad experience that I can't remember his name offhand either.
Did Harrington have a nickname?
Not as I recall it yet.
It was in the physics department and I failed the physics before I left for service, failed his class.
We had a bad experience with him.
Let's see, what were the expected rules of classroom behavior, appearance?
Had to be in uniform.
But beyond that, of course, well-shaved, haircut, and things like that, shoeshine.
But beyond that, I don't recall anything else.
Absences?
They were very definitely frowned on.
And we didn't cut many classes.
No reason to cut classes during the week if there's no place to go or nothing to do.
But Saturdays, it was very prone to be cut.
And we did cut classes occasionally to go to weekends to football games.
Sleeping?
The only class I remember sleeping in was the lecture class about physics that I failed, which is probably why I failed.
And there was an engineering drawing class called...
It wasn't engineering drawing.
It was a math course that we used.
I can't think of the name of the course.
But Ransdell was the teacher, a very good teacher, but it was right after lunch, and I couldn't stay away.
Is Charles Ransdell?
I think so.
In engineering?
Yeah.
He later became head of the, not engineering design, but what is it now?
Retired, lives in the eastern edge of Albuquerque now.
Really?
He was an excellent teacher, a nice person.
Engineering distribution, industrial distribution, he was involved in that, and my son had him as the head of those departments or something.
Let's see.
Were there any famous visitors in these pre-war months that you recall?
No, I don't ever remember recalling them.
Alright, and when y'all went, you and your friends went somewhere for excitement, other than back home, where else did y'all go?
Oh, we would go to downtown Bryan, we'd go to Eaton, Eaton, two or three cafes that were there, or we went to the movies, or we went to the campus theater, and they never will get,
My first semester, I wouldn't have thought of it if you hadn't reminded me.
The two late girls, young girls I suppose, singers, had vocal programs between movies and the campus theater at that time.
They sang it.
And one of the songs that I always remember singing, why they did it, was the Lillian Marlene.
But why they sang a German song in those years, I don't remember.
Describe the campus theater, as you would call it.
Of course, it hadn't changed.
It was still the only, except for Guy, the only theater there in the neighborhood.
I guess it had a small balcony.
I don't remember, but we all sat downstairs.
Almost all students in the audience?
Yeah, almost.
I don't remember anybody else, but I'm sure there probably were.
The building is a typical theater.
I don't know how else to describe a theater.
I guess you could call it kind of an Art Deco thing today, but I don't know if you could call it anything now.
Describe the rest of Northgate and those drugstores.
One of them was directly across the street.
I don't remember the name of that one.
And upstairs it had a...
I had some pool tables, as well as marble machines.
Behind it was Zubik's, where the uniform stores, and Lagerstein's, I think.
Hollick's?
Hollick's, instead of Lagerstein's.
Hollick's.
Zubik's and Hollick's.
Across the street from that, on the opposite side, not on the campus, was another drug store with some marble machines.
I had my first breakfast there on one Sunday.
Hot dog, ham, hotcakes, and eggs on top of the Sunday side up.
There was another place with a hamburger joint just to the south of there.
And then Lupo's was there.
And he, what did Lupo's say?
Used new books and uniforms and anything he could get us to buy.
Did y'all borrow, did you ever borrow any money from him?
No, I had an allowance.
I was fortunate to have an allowance.
What kind of?
Do you remember?
Two to five dollars a week or a month.
I don't remember now.
But I kept strict.
as I've mentioned for a while, and I think I've still got one of those summaries on what it kept for me.
What activities were held at the YMCA?
A lot of meetings were held there, class meetings.
I'm sure there were church services there on Sundays.
I don't know, they must have been.
We had no chapel.
Doesn't matter.
I really don't know.
Well, there was a bowling alley, I think, in there, too.
But I never bowled, so I never went there.
Well, all right.
Then Guyon Hall.
What held it?
Guyon was a stately building with poor acoustics and hard chairs.
And we watched the release of We've Never Been Licked there.
They had other meetings there.
Kind of the premiere?
I don't know.
Yes, it was, because they did the photography.
Describe that.
We all marched in and saw a movie, is the best I can describe it.
We were up kind of in the balcony on the left side, which would be the east side of the building, as I remember.
Dignitaries there?
I don't remember.
No, it was filmed before you got there.
It was filmed before I got there, but I think, as I recall, we had the...
A premium in there anyway.
Do you remember any reaction of you real Aggies to- Corny.
But maybe that could have come later too, I don't know.
You thought it was corny?
Yes.
That was my reaction then or later, I don't know.
But it sure definitely is.
Let's see, were there any significant speakers,
clergy, performers in Guyon that you remember during those years?
I don't remember.
They had them.
I didn't go, I guess, because I don't remember it.
Were there any religious activities held on campus?
If there were, the only place would have been in the Y, that I can recall.
I don't recall anywhere else.
They did have some.
At that time, the old synagogue was open in downtown Lyon.
They had services there.
I might have gone there one time, I think, for something.
But that was all.
Other than that, it was part of the holiday I went from home.
That was close.
And you've given a very positive reaction to me of the way you felt about the way you were treated in regard to being Jewish.
Yeah.
OK.
Tell me about the diversity of the student body.
Were there any Hispanics, any Asian that you recall?
I don't recall any Asians offhand that I can recall.
I think there were maybe a few Hispanics with the, oh I know there were because Fernando Zuniga was one of my good friends from Laredo.
Gus Celaya was another one.
C-E-L-A-Y.
C-E-L-A-Y.
Were they treated differently than you?
Not that I know about.
You don't remember any nicknames or stunts or pranks or anything?
Not that I ever was involved in or heard about.
Any Lebanese Americans?
No halibutis, no?
I don't recall anybody by those names anyway.
And was the student body, do you remember anybody notable for being rich?
Mm-mm.
Couldn't know anybody.
We were all in uniform.
And after the war, I don't remember.
I don't recall anybody having a car.
Well, there probably were some cars in those days.
Couldn't be kept on campus.
All right.
Special events.
Was silver taps held?
Silver taps was held.
Of course, that was a religious moment.
Everybody who paid strict attention to it, the whole student body, turned out for it at that time.
And the lights definitely were off.
It was held?
At the flagpole in front of the academic building, which is then Military Walk, which was a street near Roswald.
It was right in front.
Muster?
Muster.
See, I got there, and the first mustard was in April of 44.
And I didn't stay for that.
I came to Houston because a friend of mine had had brain surgery.
It was an all-sun Aggie, but he had quit school.
He quit school.
He was in the Air Force, and they laid him out because he had the brain.
He discovered the tumor at that time.
He was in the class of 45.
another friend of mine in the class of 46, and I hitchhiked home to see him.
I didn't stay for that first muster, which I always regret.
Do you remember where it was held?
Probably in Guyon, but no I don't, offhand.
We've been into Warefield House too.
Did you students, had you all heard about the Corregidor muster?
I don't think I had heard about the Corregidor muster.
I haven't run into anybody who had.
I don't think I had ever heard about the Corregidor Muster.
All right, yell practice.
Where was yell practice held?
Yell practice was on the steps of the Y.
And held when during the week?
Was it?
Probably Tuesday and Thursday, but I don't remember specifically.
But was there a midnight yell practice?
Yeah, there was midnight yell practice.
OK, and it was held there?
Yeah, it was held there.
All right, let's go.
We were serious, so let's go now to a lighter.
Tell me about, describe a football game day, home game.
Home game?
Take from the, from Friday night.
Okay, at some point, no, we didn't do that until later.
Make this T, that was later years.
First year, I don't remember anything special except the yell practice.
I don't think we marched in.
I don't think we had any kind of review.
We would go to the game.
We'd sit in front.
We'd stand as freshmen.
I'll never forget losing to Texas.
One of the Yale leaders at that time was a junior, Jack Knox, who was an association president and a renowned dermatologist, as you know.
was one of the junior Yale leaders.
And after we lost to Texas that year, I made an effort to find him and probably tell him it would get better.
And we both cried a little bit and let it go at that.
That was your first Texas game?
Yes.
No, the first Texas game as a student.
As a student, yes, yes, yes.
I had attended every, from 1939
through 1975.
I made every Texas game.
I even got on leave to go overseas in time to come to the game.
And then when I got home in time the next year to attend the game, first event I did, got home on a Thursday the game.
I mean, on a Tuesday the game.
On a Saturday the game was the following Thursday that I came home.
Jack became one of my good friends as a result of that chance meeting after the game.
You didn't have a car during those years.
Now you go away to the war.
Now you came back when?
Came back, started back to school in February of 1947.
So you were away...
I was away from...
Almost three years.
No, no.
No, no.
I was away from... Oh, no, no.
Yeah, two years.
Two years.
A year and a half.
Okay.
First of all, how had you changed?
Well, I was much more mature in that respect.
I had been in service and...
I just knew I had grown up, been in service.
Where had you served?
There was a little town called Schlangenbad in Germany, which was maybe 30 miles from Wiesbaden, maybe 50, 60 miles from Frankfurt, just a few miles from the Rhine River.
Had a nice little aviation engineer headquarters.
Our main project were to rebuild and build airfields.
I worked in operations, and we'd go into East Biden, to the American Red Cross, and it was a nice place.
I had ice cream there, fresh eggs, and in about eight months, we had got served there.
Lived in a small hotel, two-door room.
We didn't have any sheets, but we took mattress covers,
sheets out of them.
It was very nice.
We could have laundry done for a couple of weeks for a bar or so.
Buy most anything you wanted to for cigarettes.
I sent members of them.
Eventually bought things and sent home Dresden statuettes and
Knives, carving knives and things I bought with cigarettes.
My best friend there was a guy from Atlantic, Iowa.
We had our picture taken for cigarettes and gum and candy.
We had above the officer's club and headquarters, there was a swimming pool and a tennis court that we were able to use.
We had a, my first involvement with really when printing was in that, we had a printing press there that they used for maps.
Lithograph press.
Right, and you served there?
That was the only place I served actively.
So you came back then?
I came back from there, I guess my first.
And you're how, what age when you got back to Indiana?
Let's see, this was 47, so I guess I was 20.
And I got sacked.
Very mature.
And I'm thinking, I'm chuckling about the experiences you had had compared to today's 20-year-old.
Well, they were 100% different, but thank God I had them because I, between A&M and the service, I grew up.
You're still an aero engineer.
Yeah.
I still finished in aero because it was only three semesters instead of four.
Right.
Describe A&M physically then when you arrived the second time.

The mob scene because all the classes were full and the dorms were full and I went back in the corps because I wanted to get a commission and ended up rooming with Dave Schwartz from Galveston which it was an accident but it was almost a purposeful accident.
His older brother
had been in the Navy, and I knew him physically, let's say, before he left for the Navy.
So when he came back, I saw him, I knew him, and he told me that Babe had shown up on the campus.
And so I found him, and we became roommates.
And we're still best friends at this wedding.
We're still good friends.
But there was a mob scene that was all led by the big war vets.
I never felt as a war veteran because my service was so easy as compared to what they had.
And they were always the student leaders.
We had many of them.
The athletes who'd gone into service came back.
Marty Welch, Willie Zappalak.
I can't remember others right now.

But they came back and they were, a guy named Bill Andrews was the one that I remember why I don't remember his name, but we had a big meeting over something important I'm sure in the old Wooden Assembly Hall.
I don't know why I remember his name all of a sudden.
Where did the married veterans live?
They had converted dorms and
barracks that were moved in at the, I guess it was the North Gate area, some on campus and some off campus.
Were there trailers?
I don't recall any trailers.
How did you and your fellow veterans respond to a corps ritual?
By that time I was an upperclassman and a senior.
didn't bother me at all.

I participated in all the core activities until I, for the first two semesters I was back and when I had one more semester I needed, I needed two military science courses to graduate and get commissioned and other courses so I went to the commandant.
And they had permission to audit the courses and move out of the course so I could.
I took the two military science courses, I think I took 24, 25 hours that semester.
But the military science courses were easy having been in service and there weren't any problems.
And I didn't put a uniform on until I went to take the test.
I didn't have to drill because it concluded with labs.
I already had it very easy that last semester there.
So you're there how long?
Three semesters.
The last semester was the spring of about 48.
Were there any faculty members from that period that you remember?
Faculty members, advisors, counselors?
That's when I had the professor that was Dr. Riddick.
He was so spooked over, he couldn't straighten up.
It started with a B. I keep thinking of his name still.
Who was president then?
I think Gilchrist was then president.
It might have been Harrington for a while.
No, I think it was Gilchrist.
In that period of time.
The most significant things I remember were two common laws.
Though Davis had been retired or replaced for whatever reason, I don't remember.
And Gaius Malloy was a commandant and a wonderful military person who he loved to follow if he had to go to combat.
And then General Boatner, who became General Boatner, he went to Korea and settled the riots in the Korean prison camps very quickly.
Describe his personality as you knew it.
Oh, he's strong as horse radish.
stocky, very military, very, I don't want to say Germanic in his military approach, very rigid.
That's probably a better way to put it.
Now, when you get back, the freshmen are all at Bryan Field.
Weren't they there before I left, too?
I don't know.
I guess not because Bryan Field was used for
For the military at that time.
So I guess they were at Bryan Field that first semester.
Did you upperclassmen interact with them much?
Never.
We might have been good drill with them, but that may be all.
Were there still pranks and good bull with you upperclassmen only on the campus?
I don't remember any drown outs specifically that I can remember at that point.
Where I'm headed is, was there
a difference in the basic attitude of you students.
